<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="335" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,1015,1582]" pageId="6" pageNumber="335">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,308,1196,1222]" pageId="6" pageNumber="335">Remarks</emphasis>
. A very rare species known from only a few specimens, including the single specimen of the original description (see 
<bibRefCitation author="Vinogradov, M. E. &amp; Volkov, A. F. &amp; Semenova, T. N." box="[334,596,1231,1258]" pageId="6" pageNumber="335" refId="ref11020" refString="Vinogradov, M. E., Volkov, A. F. &amp; Semenova, T. N. (1996) Hyperiid amphipods (Amphipoda, Hyperiidea) of the world oceans. Oxonian Press Pvt. Ltd., New Delhi, 632 pp." type="book" year="1996">
Vinogradov 
<emphasis box="[473,522,1232,1258]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="335">et al</emphasis>
. 1996
</bibRefCitation>
). The only female collected is an adult ovigerous specimen with three relatively large eggs in the marsupium. The specimen presents the distinctive long setae extending over the pereopod 5 and pereopod 6 dactylus, it has two teeth on the anterior margin of pereopod 5 and, in general, agrees with the expected relative segment proportions of pereopods 1–7, as described and illustrated by 
<bibRefCitation author="Wagler, E." box="[1143,1308,1339,1366]" pageId="6" pageNumber="335" pagination="317 - 446" refId="ref11068" refString="Wagler, E. (1926) Amphipoda, 2: Scinidae. Wissenschaftliche Ergebnisse der deutschen Tiefsee-Expedition auf dem Dampfer &quot; Valdivia &quot; 1898 - 1899, 20 (6), 317 - 446." type="journal article" year="1926">Wagler (1926)</bibRefCitation>
. The specimen is about the same size (3.5 mm) as 
<taxonomicName authority="Gasca &amp; Hendrickx, 2020" authorityName="Gasca &amp; Hendrickx" authorityYear="2020" box="[603,719,1376,1402]" class="Malacostraca" family="Scinidae" genus="Scina" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amphipoda" pageId="6" pageNumber="335" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="trispina" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[603,719,1376,1402]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="335">S. trispina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[726,816,1376,1402]" pageId="6" pageNumber="335">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[726,816,1376,1402]" pageId="6" pageNumber="335" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
but the eggs present in the marsupium are smaller (0.2 mm) and fewer (only four were observed).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,1015,1582]" pageId="6" pageNumber="335">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Wagler" authorityYear="1926" box="[199,359,1448,1474]" class="Malacostraca" family="Scinidae" genus="Scina" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Amphipoda" pageId="6" pageNumber="335" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="setigera">
<emphasis box="[199,359,1448,1474]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="335">Scina setigera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was reported with some doubts (a damaged, immature specimen) by 
<bibRefCitation author="Siegel-Causey, D." box="[1144,1388,1447,1474]" pageId="6" pageNumber="335" refId="ref10803" refString="Siegel-Causey, D. (1982) Factors determining the distribution of hyperiid Amphipoda in the Gulf of California. Ph. D. Thesis, University of Arizona, Tucson, Arizonal, 535 pp." type="book" year="1982">Siegel-Causey (1982)</bibRefCitation>
and further records in the region (
<bibRefCitation author="Brusca, R. C. &amp; Hendrickx, M. E." box="[483,784,1483,1510]" pageId="6" pageNumber="335" pagination="139 - 154" refId="ref9496" refString="Brusca, R. C. &amp; Hendrickx, M. E. (2005) Cap. 12. Crustacea 4. Lophogastrida, Mysida, Amphipoda Tanaideacea &amp; Cumacea. In: Hendrickx, M. E., Brusca, R. C. &amp; Findley, L. T. (Eds.), A Distributional Checklist of the Macrofauna of the Gulf of California, Mexico. Part I. Invertebrates. [Listado y Distribucion de la Macrofauna del Golfo de California, Mexico, Parte I. Invertebrados]. Arizona-Sonora Desert Museum, Tucson, Arizona, pp. 139 - 154." type="book chapter" year="2005">Brusca &amp; Hendrickx 2005</bibRefCitation>
; García Madrigal 2007) were based on this unique report. The adult ovigerous specimen collected during this survey, however, confirms the presence of this species in the eastern Pacific.
</paragraph>
